snippet.textDisplay: If you want a real life recounting of what it's like to be a small platform and have one of the big dogs screw you over, here goes - I was in a touring band for near a decade. We built up a decent fan base and had some online presence. We got hacked due to a security failure, which is well documented in said "big dog" status and we tried to reclaim what was ours. We were a metal band and posted pretty consistent content. Making it obvious that what was now happening was out of character.  I tried for 2 years to get control back and we were told that it was not possible, even though their records showed it was not the same people in charge. By this time the hacker/hackers were using our platform to promote their own material and once they realised it wasn't working for them, started harassing fans and then posting very strange posts. They even started tagging us in our place of work (which is terrifying) and posting hate speech. All through this I was talking to a supposed human, which like this video had inconsistencies that made me believe (and ask) if I was speaking to a human. I was also told that there was no person to speak too on the phone, regardless of evidence i supplied and ended in "unless you have a subpoena , don't bother" The only way we could get a bit of control back in the end was to use a DMC take down for our images. Which all had to be done individually as they did not recognise the group as a whole. I have all of this documented if you would like to look at any of it.

snippet.textDisplay:
Like MXRPlays.. they've been fighting for a long time with YouTube over monetization and what is basically extortion for thousands of dollars over some scam company claiming bs rights to their videos.. but YouTube is making it so much worse by their avoidance of problems and not really getting involved to solve anything.
To be honest.. I think YouTube knows exactly what they're doing. This is the result they want. Even if it's a clusterfuck, negative attention is still attention. And usually it's a lot more attention than the positive kind. And look at the results. Look at how much audience engagement is happening because of the clusterfuck. YouTubers' audiences are having to speak up and get involved and raise hell on behalf of their favorite creators. So much more engagement than before, and at the same time, to me it seems like many creators are being humbled, more like extremely anxious and desperate because their livelihood is being ripped away, and maybe YouTube wants this. Maybe they think they're keeping the creators 'in line'? But what would they gain? Wouldn't YouTubers just quit? Wouldn't they go to other platforms where their fans could become direct patrons instead? Maybe YouTube is banking on that other platforms aren't asfull proof, reliable, or that their size and power can be used to crush the competition.
I rarely comment to be honest, but I've been observing this quietly for awhile, and a few YouTubers I like enough, for their senses of humor and for who they seem to be as people, to want to help, if possible, so I'm here jotting this down with a hellacious migraine..
Welp, gonna copy and paste this to those few YouTubers across the different social medias, because of said pain, and depression is a bitch. What's up MXR Plays/Jeanie and Henry, Daz Games/Daz Black, Phil DeFranco, Markiplier, HellFreezer, MortisMedia, Updoot Reddit, and Shane Dawson.. conspiracy theory? Lol ;)

snippet.textDisplay:
) One month after the city of Wuhan was put on lockdown, the coronavirus infection cases and death tolls are still on the rise every day.

In Wuhan, a city home to 11 million people, the streets are still empty and the shops remain closed. All social activities have come to a halt. No one anticipates a quick end to the lockdown.

People are afraid of talking to each other, fearing becoming infected.

According to an internal document by the Hubei Communications Administration obtained by the Epoch Times, there are still about 25,000 people fleeing Wuhan every day, despite the strict travel ban, as indicated by the local residents’ cellphone geolocations.

But those who managed to escape are often met with hostility in other provinces. Some were reported and then arrested. Some were forcibly sent to hospitals, even if they weren’t showing any symptoms or confirmed to have the virus.

According to a video circulating online, one Wuhan resident who escaped to neighboring Hunan province was arrested. The local resident who reported him said, “It’s not that I didn’t want to be nice to you, but you came from Wuhan and I’m afraid of death.”

The coronavirus outbreak has brought out the worst in some people.

According to an article titled “Chinese city accused of stealing virus masks from hard-hit neighbour” by Reuters on February 6, the city of Dali in Yunnan Province intercepted hundreds of boxes of surgical masks bound for Chongqing.

Similar incidents were also reported in Dalian and Shenyang, Liaoning Province and Qingdao, Shandong Province.

From “Controllable and Preventable” to Complete Lockdown
On January 19, Li Gang, director and chief physician for the Wuhan Center for Disease Control and Prevention, said during a press conference that the epidemic was “preventable and controllable.”

Four days later, the authorities in Wuhan suddenly announced the lockdown of the city. All public transportation, including buses, subways, trains, ferries, and flights, was suspended.

Days later, more cities in Hubei Province, including Ezhou, Huanggang, Chibi, Xiantao, Zhijiang, Qianjjiang, Xianning, Jingmen, Dangyang, Huangshi, Enshi, and Xiaogan, were also put on lockdown.
